   363→
   364→            <h2>Proof Strategy</h2>
   365→
   366→            <p>
   367→                The verification establishes that rotated roots and Chebyshev roots share identical power sums for all
   368→                positive degrees, which by Newton's identities implies they generate polynomials differing only by a
   369→                constant term. This approach reduces the geometric claim to an algebraic invariant (power sums), then
   370→                applies classical polynomial algebra to reach the conclusion.
   371→            </p>
   372→
   373→            <h3>Critical Proofs</h3>
   374→
   375→            <p>
   376→                <strong>Power Sum Invariance (<a href="./docs/ChebyshevCircles/PowerSums.html#powerSumCos_invariant" style="color: #3498db;">powerSumCos_invariant</a>):</strong>
   377→                The cornerstone of the entire proof. This establishes that ∑cos<sup>m</sup>(φ + 2πk/N) is independent of the
   378→                rotation angle φ for all m ≥ 1. The proof exploits the fact that cos(θ) = (e<sup>iθ</sup> + e<sup>-iθ</sup>)/2,
   379→                converting cosine powers into sums of complex exponentials. These exponential sums telescope to zero by discrete
   380→                orthogonality unless specific divisibility conditions hold, yielding the φ-independence. Without this result,
   381→                there would be no connection between rotated roots and Chebyshev polynomials.
   382→            </p>
   383→
   384→            <p>
   385→                <strong>Discrete Orthogonality (<a href="./docs/ChebyshevCircles/ChebyshevOrthogonality.html" style="color: #3498db;">ChebyshevOrthogonality module</a>):</strong>
   386→                Proves that ∑<sub>k=0</sub><sup>N-1</sup> exp(2πikm/N) = 0 for 0 < m < N and equals N when m = 0 or N divides m.
   387→                This is the discrete analog of continuous Fourier orthogonality on the circle. The proof uses properties of
   388→                geometric series and the fact that N-th roots of unity satisfy ω<sup>N</sup> = 1. This orthogonality is what
   389→                causes most terms in the power sum expansion to vanish, leaving only the φ-independent contributions. It connects
   390→                harmonic analysis (orthogonality relations) to polynomial root behavior.
   391→            </p>
   392→
   393→            <p>
   394→                <strong>Newton's Identities (<a href="./docs/ChebyshevCircles/NewtonIdentities.html" style="color: #3498db;">NewtonIdentities module</a>):</strong>
   395→                Establishes the relationship between power sums of roots and elementary symmetric polynomials (coefficients).
   396→                Specifically, if two monic polynomials have roots with matching power sums S<sub>1</sub>, S<sub>2</sub>, ..., S<sub>N</sub>,
   397→                then the polynomials have identical coefficients except possibly the constant term. This is the bridge that converts
   398→                power sum equality into polynomial equality up to a constant. The formalization handles the recursive structure
   399→                of Newton's identities and proves the converse direction needed: power sum agreement implies coefficient agreement.
   400→                This classical result from polynomial algebra is indispensable for connecting root properties to polynomial identity.
   401→            </p>
   402→
   403→            <h2>Getting Started</h2>
   404→
   405→            <p>
   406→                <strong>Prerequisites:</strong> Lean 4 (v4.25.0-rc2), basic familiarity with polynomials, complex numbers,
   407→                and trigonometric identities.
   408→            </p>
   409→
   410→            <p>
   411→                Clone the repository and build the project:
   412→            </p>
   413→
   414→            <div class="theorem-statement">
   415→git clone https://github.com/e-vergo/ChebyshevCircles.git<br>
   416→cd ChebyshevCircles<br>
   417→lake exe cache get<br>
   418→lake build
   419→            </div>
   420→
